ce:section.ce:para:
In the analysis of actual samples, the determination of DOX in urine and serum may suffer from interfering substances. The common cations and anions (K+, Na+, Ca2+, Fe3+, Zn2+, Mg2+, SO4
                        2−, Cl−) can be found in human serum and urine. In addition, some amino acids (glycine, glutamic acid, proline, threonine, valine, histidine), nucleosides (5-methyluridine, adenosine, cytidine, guanosine, thymidine), biological molecules (present in serum) and uric acid (present in urine) may interfere with the determination of DOX. Fig. S6 is the UV–vis absorption spectra of interference substances. There is no overlap between the absorption peaks of interfering substances and the emission peak of PCQDs except for DOX. Upon mixing the interfering substances with the probe, only DOX could significantly increase the I591/I491 of PCQDs, whereas other interfered substances have no obvious effect on I591/I491 (Fig. 5
                        ). This indicates that the detection of DOX is not interfered by the tested substances. Liao et al. reported a water-soluble CdS quantum dots for the detection of DOX, in which Cu2+ and Fe3+ interfere with the analysis results [9]. In contrast, the probe in this work is not interfered by Cu2+ and Fe3+. In clinic, DOX is often used together with some drugs for cancer treatment, i. e, cytarabine, cytoxan, 5-fluorouracil and methotrexate. Meng et al. used the gold/silver nanoclusters as a fluorescence probe for the detection of DOX, but this probe has response to methotrexate, thus interfering with the detection of DOX [10]. To study the selectivity of fluorescence sensor, cytarabine, cytoxan, 5-fluorouracil and methotrexate were selected as competitors. As shown in Fig. S7, the four combined drugs cannot affect the values of I591/I491, indicating the fluorescence sensor shows good selectivity to DOX. The good selectivity is attributed to the reason that this ratio fluorescence probe can eliminate the interferences.
